***************************************************************************
                              Making Weapons
***************************************************************************
Note: All literal code in this help document is separated by a bunch of =
signs. The = signs are NOT part of the code. For example:

====================
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
#include <material.h>
====================

refers to the three include lines, literally.


***************************************************************************
                              Basic Weapons
***************************************************************************
A basic acceptable weapon inherits WEAPON and sets a few parameters.
Your weapon file MUST have the following lines of code at the top:

====================
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
#include <material.h>
inherit WEAPON;
====================

If you want to put in comments before these lines, that's fine, but
these MUST precede any active code in the file.

Your weapon MUST haved a reset function, with appropriate checks for
clones. That is, it must have the code:

====================
void reset(int iArg) {
    if (!is_clone(this_object())) return;
    ::reset(iArg);
    if (iArg) return;
====================

Even a basic weapon has to have a few settings to make it interesting.
You should have the following settings for your weapon:

set_short("short");
        Replace "short" with the quoted short description of your weapon.
        The short description is the one a player sees when an object
        is just lying on the ground, in a shop, in someone's inventory etc.

set_long("long.\n");
        Replace "long" with the quoted long description of your weapon.
        The long description is the one a player sees when he actually
        does a 'look' or 'examine' on an object. Remember to add both a
        period and a newline (\n) at the end of your description since
        LPC won't do that for you.

set_name("name");
        Replace "name" with the quoted name of your weapon. This name
        should be the main name by which your weapon is called, since it
        may show up on occasion in spam to players. It should never be
        a secret id key used to uniquely identify it for coding purposes.
        For example, "bobs_magic_sword_key" is a terrible name for a
        weapon. It is often a good idea to use the short description of
        the weapon as its name as well, but always use all lowercase
        letters and no articles. (e.g. "silver longsword" is good, but
        "a silver longsword" or "Silver Longsword" are bad).

set_alias("alias");
        Replace "alias" with the quoted alias of your weapon. This alias
        can be any other way to refer to a weapon. For example, if you
        had a silver longsword with the name "silver longsword" you would
        also want to have the aliases "silver sword", "longsword" and
        "sword" as aliases. If you want to use a secret id key to uniquely
        identify your weapon, you can use set it as an alias. You can add
        multiple aliases by using this setting over and over again. This
        setting is optional.        

set_new_type(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc.);
        Replace TYPE1|TYPE2|etc. with an ORed set of weapon type values.
        That is, something that looks like:  MEDIUM|SLASH|PIERCE
        Exactly one of the values must be a size (SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE,
        or HUGE) and at least one value must be a weapon damage type
        (SLASH, PIERCE, BLUNT or CLEAVE). Other acceptable components
        are: TWO_HANDED, POLE and MISSILE.

set_material(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc.);
        Replace TYPE1|TYPE2|etc. with an ORed set of material values.
        That is, something that looks like:  MAT_STEEL|MAT_WOOD
        Valid material types are listed in the material documentation,
        wizhelp 4.16 'materials'.

set_material_composition(TYPE);
        Replace TYPE with the material type which characterizes the
        'business end' of the weapon. Thus for a steel sword with a
        wooden hilt, you would set_material(MAT_STEEL|MAT_WOOD); and
        set_material_composition(MAT_STEEL); since the wood is not
        particularly relevant to the cutting edge. Material composition
        ratings for weapons can be found in /open/INCLUDE/weapon_stats.h.
        NB your TYPE can ONLY be a single type. A composite type like
        MAT_STEEL|MAT_SILVER will not work. There is an additional syntax
        available if you absolutely want to use multiple types in your
        composition. Replace TYPE with a type:percetage mapping to use
        that syntax. For example:
        set_material_composition(([MAT_STEEL:40, MAT_SILVER:60]));

set_quality(quality);
        Replace quality with an integer quality value from -100 to 100.
        Quality is how good your weapon is, compared to other weapons
        of the given composition. A quality of 0 is average, and a quality
        of 100 is the best of the best. A -100 quality would be something
        laughably bad (like a bent spoon maybe). Any weapon with a
        quality of greater than 40 is considered at least exceptional.
        Any with a quality greater than 60 is unique. (see also wizhelp
        4.14 'uniques'). Typical factors that should affect quality are:
        craftsmanship, wear/damage, rust, non-weapon types (things that
        are not usually weapons such as pitchforks), extra hurty bits
        (knobs, spikes, flanges), odd shape, balance etc.

set_weight(weight);
        Replace weight with an integer weight value. This is the weight 
        of the object. Weight on Darkwind also represents bulk and
        awkwardness of carrying.
        |000|CKBIf you want to have the game set a standard weight, you can|000
        |000|CKBset_weight(query_equipment_weight()); You need to use that after|000
        |000|CKByou have set_new_type() and set_material().|000

set_value(-1);
        Weapon values are automatically determined by the characteristics
        of the weapon. Do not set a value for basic weapons. (The -1
        means to use the automatically generated value) NOTE: this
        should be the very last function called in your reset function.

That's it! An example basic weapon is given in
/open/EXAMPLES/WEAPONS/basic_weapon.c

If all you want is to make a basic weapon, copy that file to directory
where your area's weapons are, and replace all the content values (e.g.
the quoted text used for set_long(), set_short() etc.) with your own
stuff.


***************************************************************************
                              Extra Settings
***************************************************************************
The following extra settings can be used in your weapon as well, but are
not required:

set_read("text.\n");
        Replace "text.\n" with the quoted string to be seen when the
        weapon is read. It there is writing on the blade of a sword, for
        example, you may wish to use this. Remember to add both a period
        and a newline (\n) at the end of your description since LPC won't
        do that for you.

set_info("info.\n");
        Replace "info.\n" with the quoted string to be seen when a mage
        or such identifies the weapon. It should NEVER give specific
        numbers but it should give enough information for a person to get
        a fair idea of a weapons strengths or powers.

set_no_buy();
        Put this in if this weapon cannot be bought from the shop. (After
        someone has sold it as loot.)

set_no_sell(sell_setting);
        Replace sell_setting with an integer. If sell_setting is 1, the
        item will be marked as unsellable. If it is 0, it will clear
        a previously set sell_setting of 1. If you use a sell_setting
        greater than 1, then it will take that many calls of
        set_sell(0); to make it sellable again.

set_steal(1 or 0);
        If set_steal(1); is used, the weapon is not stealable. If you
        set_steal(0); the weapon will be stealable by thieves. Yes, it
        seems backwards and very stupid, which it is, but it is correct.

set_cursed(curse_chance);
        Replace curse_chance by an integer percentage indicating the
        likelihood of any clone of this weapon being cursed. If this line
        is not used, objects will default to a 1% chance of being cursed.

set_no_curse();
        Put this line in if you want the weapon to never be cursed. This
        should be used very sparingly. It will prevent the 1% chance that
        any given weapon or armour in the game will be cursed.  It should
        be stressed that this should only be set on items that under no
        circumstances should be cursed. I.e. quest items, a holy defender
        unique sword etc.

set_value(-1, ##);
        Replace ## by an integer value to INCREASE the value of this weapon
        above the default value. Use this instead of the normal call to
        set_value(-1); if you want your weapon to be extra valuable.

set_damage_type(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc..);
        Replace TYPE1|TYPE2|etc. with an ORed set of damage types.
        That is, something that looks like:  DAM_GOOD|DAM_FIRE
        Valid damage types are listed in the damage type documentation,
        wizhelp 4.17 'damage types'. Do not use this to set the standard
        weapon damage types set by set_new_type().

set_hit_bonus(bonus)
        Replace bonus with a integer value. The weapon's hit bonus
        increases the wielder's hitting stat (average of dex, int) while
        using this weapon. A negative value will reduce the wielder's
        hitting stat. This is a very powerful ability and should be used
        sparingly. (A 6 point increase is roughly equivalent to a level's
        increase in stats) Weapons with a hit_bonus are considered
        exceptional or unique; see wizhelp 4.14 'uniques' for details.

set_guild_allow(GUILD|GUILD|...);
        Replace GUILD|GUILD|... with an ORed set of guild defines (from
        guildd.h) which indicate which guilds are allowed to use this
        weapon, weapon restrictions notwithstanding. In order to use this
        setting, you must include guildd.h at the beginning of your file.
 
set_guild_restrict(GUILD|GUILD|...);
        This function is the same as set_guild_allow() except it will
        disallow the use of that particular weapon by the guilds you have
        listed.


***************************************************************************
                              Hit/Wield Functions
***************************************************************************
Hitting and wielding functions cause things to happen when the weapon
hits in combat, or is wielded. This is useful for example, if you want
to give some spam in combat, or extra bonuses, or if you want to give
the player a stat boost when wielding it.

set_hit_func(oFuncObject);
        Pass the object that defines weapon_hit() (explained below) as
        oFuncObject. In most cases, oFuncObject this_object(). Whenever a
        hit is made in combat, oFuncObject->weapon_hit(oTarget); will be
        called with oTarget being the current target of the hit.

int weapon_hit(oTarget);
        This function is defined in the oFuncObject passed to
        set_hit_func(). Usually both functions are in the weapon anyway.
        This function gets called if the set_hit_func() was set, and
        a player/monster has made a swing, and actually made contact
        (not dodged). It is the builder's job to fill out this function
        with whatever special things that are to happen. The
        returned value is a bonus applied to the wielder's damage stat,
        for that hit. Use of this function almost always make this weapon
        a unique-class weapon, so be warned and ask questions before using
        it. See wizhelp 4.14 'uniques' for guidelines on special hits.)

        A weapon using set_hit_func() must declare its scripted hit value
        for gearcheck with add_power_feature("scripted_hit", ...). See
        wizhelp 4.26 for the equipment power API and examples.

set_wield_func(oFuncObject);
        Pass the object that defines wield_func() and unwield_func()
        (explained below) as oFuncObject. In most cases, oFuncObject
        this_object(). Whenever the weapon is wielded oFuncObject->
        wield_func(this_object()) will be called, and whenever unwielded,
        oFuncObject->unwield_func(this_object()) will be called.

int wield_func(oWeapon);
        This function is defined in the oFuncObject passed to
        set_wield_func(). Usually both functions are in the weapon anyway.
        This function gets called if the set_wield_func() was set, and
        a player/monster tries to wield this weapon. It is the builder's
        job to fill out the this function with whatever special things
        that are to happen. If this function returns 0, then the wield
        will fail. Thus you can use this to block a weapon being wielded
        by certain people.    

int unwield_func(oWeapon);
        This function is defined in the oFuncObject passed to
        set_wield_func(). Usually both functions are in the weapon anyway.
        This function gets called if the set_wield_func() was set, and
        a player/monster tries to unwield this weapon. It is the builder's
        job to fill out the this function with whatever special things
        that are to happen. If this function returns 0, then the unwield
        will fail.

        A weapon with a scripted wield effect must declare that effect for
        gearcheck with add_power_feature("scripted_wield", ...). See
        wizhelp 4.26.

|CKBvoid add_equipment_stat(string sStat, int iValue, string sStart, string sStop);|XX0
        This function will handle adding the stat sStat to the
        player when they wield the item, and remove the stat when
        the player unwields the item. It eliminates the need of
        creating start_wearing/stop_wearing functions in the item.
        sStat can be "con","dex","int","wis","str","chr","hp","sp",
      |RK0    "tmp_to_hit_stat","tmp_to_dam_stat","tmp_to_dodge_stat",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_absorb_stat","tmp_to_crit_stat","tmp_to_swings",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_hit","tmp_to_dam","tmp_to_dodge","tmp_to_absorb",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_crit","tmp_to_type"|XX0
      |RK0    tmp_to_* should only be used with permission.|XX0
        sStart is the message when the player wears the armor.
        sStop is the message when the player stops wearing the armor.
        The message is in the same format as room_message.
      |RK0  The messages should only be used once per item, not stat.|XX0
    |GKBExample:|XX0add_equipment_stat("con",5,"$N $vseem hardier.",
        "$N $vseem less robust.");
